In biology, '''genetic demixing'''<ref>{{cite journal |title= Genetic demixing and evolution in linear stepping stone models| journal= Reviews of Modern Physics| volume= 82| issue= 2| pages= 1691| date= 2010| doi= 10.1103/RevModPhys.82.1691 | pmid= 21072144|arxiv=0904.4625v2| last1= Korolev| first1= K. S.| last2= Avlund| first2= Mikkel| last3= Hallatschek| first3= Oskar| last4= Nelson| first4= David R.| pmc=2975585| bibcode= 2010RvMP...82.1691K}}</ref> refers to a phenomenon in which an initial mixture of individuals with
two or more distinct [[genotypes]] rearranges in the course of time,
giving birth to a spatial organization where some or all genotypes are concentrated in distinct patches.

